      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1404">
               <p>A native of <placeName>Bristol</placeName>, Maxfield was converted by
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2221.xml"/>Whitefield</persName> in
                     <date when="1739">1739</date> in the earliest stages of the revival. Maxfield
                  began assisting <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> with
                  pastoral duties there, and followed <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> to <placeName>London</placeName>, where he became a trusted
                  leader at the Foundery. During one of <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s absences, Maxfield
                  ventured to preach, though a layman. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> initially resisted this innovation, until his mother
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2193.xml"/>Susanna</persName> convinced
                  him in <date when="1741">1741</date> that Maxfield was &apos;a son in the
                  gospel&apos;. He then embraced Maxfield as the first lay traveling preacher.
                  Maxfield was later ordained at <placeName>Bath</placeName> by the Bishop of Derry,
                  to assist <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>. Maxfield
                  was trusted by <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and
                  central to deliberations in Conference for two decades. But in the early
                     <date>1760s</date> he took the side of the perfectionist party in
                     <placeName>London</placeName>. This led to a break from <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>, with Maxfield setting up an
                  independent chapel. The breach was only minimally healed in the following years.
                  Maxfield married <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1403.xml"/>Elizabeth
                     Branford</persName> on <date when="1749-12-21">Dec. 21, 1749</date>, in
                     <placeName>London</placeName>. See Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>,
                  266–69; <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 756–57; Pawson, <hi rend="italic"
                  >Letters</hi>, 3:143; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 225.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
